  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This study explores how RadD from <em>Fusobacterium nucleatum</em> interacts with the NKp46 receptor to enhance antitumor cytotoxicity, representing a novel approach in cancer immunotherapy. The collaborative research was conducted by experts at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem and UCLA Health, supported by significant funding from various Israeli agencies.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research titled \"RadD from <em>Fusobacterium nucleatum</em> Engages NKp46 to Promote Antitumor Cytotoxicity\" delves into the mechanisms behind enhanced immune responses in cancer therapy. By identifying the interaction between RadD and NKp46, the authors contribute valuable insights into how bacterial components may augment natural killer cell activity against tumors.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This work is grounded in substantial institutional support, with primary affiliations at Hebrew University of Jerusalem and UCLA Health. Such esteemed universities underscore the significance of this research within the broader context of immunology and cancer treatment strategies, validating the scientific inquiry into novel immune modulators.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the early sharing of this research via a preprint has not yet seen public engagement through downloads or citations, the act of disseminating findings prior to formal publication demonstrates the authors' commitment to open science. Such practices facilitate early feedback and encourage community involvement, an essential step for accelerating research translation into clinical applications.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the backing from the Israeli Innovation Authority and the Israel Science Foundation highlights a robust investment in advancing biomedical research in Israel. This funding not only supports innovative projects like this one but also enhances the research landscape by fostering collaborative efforts among leading institutions.</p>",
